 habitats are unlikely to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">reflect the original fine scale conditions </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">necessary for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">certain species.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There are gaps in knowledge </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">about the biology of some </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">species</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and this </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">will affect the suc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cess of offsetting</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">schemes. A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s we don’t know what they nee</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d to complete a full life cycle</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> it is very difficult to successfully replace what has been lost</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; fo