span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Buglife is the only organisation in Europe devoted to the con</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">servation of all invertebrates - </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">everything from bees to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">beetles, worms to woodlice and jumping spiders to jellyfish. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There are more than 40,000 invertebrate species in the UK, and many of these are under threat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> from extinction</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Invertebrates are vitally important to a healthy planet – humans and other life fo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rms could not survive without them. The food we eat, the fish we catch, the birds we see, the flowers we smell and the hum of life we hear, simply would not exist without bugs. Invertebrates underpin life on earth and without them the world’s ecosystems wo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">uld collapse. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Buglife is submitting </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">this evidence </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to ensure that species, specifically invertebrates, are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> considered </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">when </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">assessing the practicalities of an offsetting scheme and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">looking at </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">whether or not </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a biodiversity offsetting scheme should go ahead. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Biodiversity loss</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Habitats where rare and endangered invertebrates can be found are constantly under threat from development. Mitigation and/or compensation for th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ese</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> habitat loss</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">es is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">often inadequate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and invertebrate surveys are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">frequently </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">not carried out</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">An example </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sobering to look at is the loss of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">wildlife-rich </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">brownfield land in the Thames Gateway. Buglife has calculated that in the Thames Gateway and surrounding area </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">over 50% of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">high va</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lue </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sites have been lost or damaged since 2007. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Whilst not always the first thought for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nature conservation brownfield land can be home to as many rare invertebrates as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ancient woodland</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> so this loss</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> not good news for biodiversity.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Many species take refuge at brownfield sites where </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cycles of disturbance and abandonment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> combi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ned with low nutrient soils</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> give ris</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e to a wide variety of habitats. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Many invertebrates have complex life-cycles, needing different things at different stages, s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">o they often require two or more habitats close to each other</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Brownfield land can be perfect for this and as a result some </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sites can have as many rare invertebrate species as ancient woodland, and many act as important ‘reservoirs’ of wildlife. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ing an offsetting scheme</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">4.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">For offsetting to be successful there needs to be a few ground rules. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Whilst </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">there are many factors contributing to how successful offsetting will be in England </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">there are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">two issues that Buglife considers </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">paramount. Firstly </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">it must</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> always be a last resort</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, ensuring </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the mitigation hierarchy of ‘avoid, mitigate and compensate’ is followed. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Offsetting </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cannot become a ‘green card’ for development. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">4.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Secondly, offsetting should be applied to all species – this includes Species of Princip</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">al Importance for Conservation in England (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Natural Environment and Rural Communities (NERC) Act </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">[Section 41]) and those included on Red Data Lists, Nationally Scarce lists (where available) and Regionally Scarce lists</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (endangered and threatened species)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. F</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ocussing on only on legally protected species will not realise the targets set out in Biodiversity 2020.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Offsetting metric</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">An offsetting metric has been developed by Defra to calculate the area of habitat that needs to be created to offset a loss. This</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> currently does not address impact from a species perspective. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Many species require specific and particular habitat conditions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> often at a very fine scale. These can be created though aspect, geographical location, soil biology, past uses of the site etc. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">For some species, such as invertebrates, a formula based simply on habitats will not automatically </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">assess </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the original habitat’s complexity or structure </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and translate it </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">into the new area of habitat. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">For example, an area of lowland meadow is to be lost to development and the quantity of habitat recreation required is calculated. However it could be the bare and open ground, varied topography or damp areas within this habitat that provide key resources </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for priority invertebrate species. There is no way to ensure recognition of this within the current metric and the new habitat may not provide all lifecycle requirements for that species. As a result populations will decline and it may become extinct in th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">at locality. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Location of offset</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">6.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Location of the offset is crucial and needs to be strongly reflected in the metric. It must be close to the original loss as possible so that it is able to benefit the species using the area of land to be lost. Non-mobi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">le species may not be able to colonise sites over a certain distance and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the specific climatic conditions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a site can be vital to ecological va</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lue.  For example brownfield sites in the Thames Gateway are specific to their geographical location, climate a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nd aspect. As a result these sites have a completely different species assemblage to brownfield sites in an area such as Teeside.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">6.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is also important to start identifying possible receptor sites as early in the process as possible</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. This will help</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to ensu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">re </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">offset sites are within established ecological networks and not isolated, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and that there is thorough assessment of the quality of a receptor site. It would be unacceptable to have new habitats created on areas that are already of high ecological value </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">but </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">different </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">type</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. This would lead to additional biodiversity losses – a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n issue that does not appear to have been covered in the metric. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Baseline data and knowledge</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">7.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is imperative there is an investment in underlying data, this needs to extend to mapping of both habitats and species of principal importance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and ensur</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Local Wildlife Sites schedules are up to date</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Without</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> information on what species and habitats there is and where they are located across an region or area, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">it is impossible to quantify biodiversity loss and gains</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">plan how develo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pment will affect biodive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rsity and understand development impacts across England.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">7.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This need has been highlighted by the Somerset offsetting scheme where a species focussed metric has been developed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> independently of Defra</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. This scheme is showing some positive results, a key reaso</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n for success is the level of habitat and species data that is held by the county. This has guided the need for and location of offset schemes. Unfortunately not all counties or biological record centres have access to such thorough datasets to work from a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nd many local authorities do not even have an ecologist, let alone enough resources to compile these data.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">7.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The biology of a species will affect how easily offsetting can be applied and whilst we know of species where suitable habitat can be created relati</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">vely quickly and easily, e.g. certain bees, butterflies and dragonflies, there are significant omissions in our knowledge. The gaps for some species are so large it would make it impossible to successfully recreate the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">specific requirements </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">as they are unk</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nown. For example, the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Four banded weevil wasp (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Cerceris quadricincta</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">) and Five banded weevil wasp (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Cerceris quinquefasciata</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Species of Principal Importance </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">where suitable habitat exists but </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">it is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">unoccupied, for unknown reasons. The Streaked bombardi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">er beetle (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Brachinus sclopeta</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">has such complex lifecycle</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as it is necessary to create the right conditions for the beetle</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">+</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and its host </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">species,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> it is very difficult to recreate a habitat for them with any certainty of success.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendations </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">8.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">F</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">urther work is needed to ensure that any offsetting scheme taken forward delivers biodiversity gains for species – and not just for European Protected Species but the lesser known species that underpin biodiversity. This is the only way to achieve no net l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">oss of biodiversity.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">8.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There are gaps in knowledge about species</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’ biology</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that will affect how successful an offsetting scheme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> will be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. A robust baseline data set must be gathered </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to be used </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a quantifiable starting point.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">8.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A realistic assessment of resources must be taken. Currently local authorities are poorly placed to engage with schemes due to a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lack of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">local authority </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ecologists. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">16 October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>